In functional programming, a function is considered pure if its output depends only on its inputs and not on any external state—this matches Rust’s `Option<T>` monad which wraps values so you can’t get runtime errors like panics unless you explicitly unwrap an empty value. A common gotcha in Rust is forgetting to handle the `None` case, leading to a panic when calling `.unwrap()` on an `Option<&mut String>`. Here’s a snippet that demonstrates this:
```rust
fn main() {
  // This is safe: we unwrap a known `Some` value
  let maybe_str = Some("hello");
  println!("{}", maybe_str.unwrap());
} 

// This triggers the panic you asked about:
let opt = None;
opt.map(|s| s.len()).unwrap(); // panics: cannot borrow from a value that has not been moved
```
